# Project Overview

Nicaragua is a small open economy in Central America. Its banking sector is also small and shallow, yet it ranks among the most profitable in the region. This project aims to provide a detailed characterization of Nicaraguaâ€™s banking system, using publicly available data. It leverages the R programming language for data processing and Tableau for interactive data visualization.

The associated GitHub repository includes the following components::

-   R script for downloading and preprocessing banking data from SIBOIF. â€” [[code]](https://github.com/bejarano-ch/Nicaraguan-Banking-System-Indicators/blob/main/codes/download_data_SIBOIF.R)
-   R script for downloading official exchange-rate data from the BCN. â€” [[code]](https://github.com/bejarano-ch/Nicaraguan-Banking-System-Indicators/blob/main/codes/download_exchange_rate.R)
-   Interactive Tableau dashboards:
    -   Statement of Financial Position â€” [\[landscape\]](https://public.tableau.com/app/profile/christian.bejarano5490/viz/StatementofFinancialPosition/Landscape) [\[portrait\]](https://public.tableau.com/app/profile/christian.bejarano5490/viz/StatementofFinancialPosition/Portrait)
    -   Income Statement â€” [\[landscape\]](https://public.tableau.com/app/profile/christian.bejarano5490/viz/IncomeStatement_17496622854550/Landscape) [\[portrait\]](https://public.tableau.com/app/profile/christian.bejarano5490/viz/IncomeStatement_17496622854550/Portrait)

## Description of the data

The information is primarily sourced from the Superintendency of Banks and Other Financial Institutions (SIBOIF), through the JSON API provided by the institution. The analysis covers the period from January 2019 to the most recent available data and includes disaggregated financial position and income statement data for all supervised institutions. The objective is to expand this repository by integrating additional information from other reports, such as financial indicators and system stratifications.

## Key Insights as of May 2025

### Assets

-   The Nicaraguan banking system holds USD 9,851.7 million in total assetsâ€”roughly 50 percent of the countryâ€™s 2024 GDPâ€”and remains a traditional model, with its loan portfolio accounting for 61.2 percent of those assets.
-   The banking loan portfolio has recorded accelerated growth since 2022, reaching its highest year-on-year growth rate in February 2025 at 20.6 percent. As of May 2025, the loan balance stands at USD 6,034.1 million.
-   The credit market is dominated by three institutionsâ€”BANPRO, BAC, and LAFISEâ€”which together account for 80 percent of the systemâ€™s total loan portfolio balance.

### Liabilities and equity

-   Total liabilities of the system amount to USD 8,111.1 million. The main source of funding for the banking system is public deposits, which totaled USD 7,004.6 million (86.4 percent of total liabilities) and have registered double-digit year-on-year growth rates since 2020.
-   The sustained growth of public deposits has allowed the banking system to reduce its indebtedness to other financial institutions and expand its credit and investment operations.
-   Equity stands at USD 1,740.6 million, implying an asset-to-equity ratio of 5.65 times. Equity has recorded sustained year-on-year growth of around 10 percent, driven by increasing profitability.

